* On a longer timescale, we should aim to prove the
  [Schwartz Kernel Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwartz_kernel_theorem), which is
  formulated nicely in terms of vector-valued distributions. Indeed, it says precisely that one
  can (algebraically, at least) identify the spaces `­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓЂ ├Ќ╦б ╬ЕРѓѓ, РёЮ)` and `­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓЂ, ­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓѓ, РёЮ))`.

### Choice of scalar field

In the literature, it is common to define complex-valued distributions as continuous `Рёѓ`-linear
forms `T : ­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ) РєњL[Рёѓ] Рёѓ`. We use `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL[РёЮ] Рёѓ` instead, that is, we only ever test
against *real-valued* test functions.

This makes no difference mathematically, since `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ)` is the complexification of `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)`,
hence there is a topological isomorphism between `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL[РёЮ] F` and `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ) РєњL[Рёѓ] F`
whenever `F` is a complex vector space.

We choose this definition because it avoids adding a base field as an extra parameter.
Instead, we use the generality of vector-valued distributions to our advantage: a complex-valued
distribution is nothing more than a distribution taking values in the real vector-space `Рёѓ`.

### Order of distributions

Based on established practice in the literature, a natural way to express the order of a
distribution would be to introduce a predicate `Distribution.HasOrderAtMost` on the space of all
distributions. Here though, we define a separate space `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` whose elements are precisely
distributions of order at most `n`.

This is not incompatible with the predicate approach: in fact, we think that such a predicate
should eventually become the primary interface for the order of a distribution. However, we believe
that being able to talk about the space `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` is also quite important, for the following
reasons:
* if `T : ­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е,F)` is a distribution whose order is at most `n`, it is natural to test it against
  a `C^n` test function (especially if `n = 0`). This means that we naturally want to consider its
  extension `T'` as an element of `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)`.
* it is often quite easy to keep track of the regularities while *defining* an operation on
  distributions (e. g. differentiation). On the other hand, once you have defined an operation on
  `­ЮЊЊ'^(╬Е, F)`, it can be quite painful to study its relation to order *a posteriori*.

Note that the topology on `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` has no reason to be the subspace topology coming from
`­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)`.

### Choice of topology

Our choice of the compact convergence topology on `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` follows
[L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*, ┬Д2, p. 49][schwartz1957].

Note that, since `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)` is a Montel space, the topology on `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` is also that of
bounded convergence. Hence, our definition also agrees with
[L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д3][schwartz1950].

When `n` is finite, however, `­ЮЊЊ^{n}(╬Е, РёЮ)` is no longer a Montel space
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д2, p. 71][schwartz1950]), hence
these two topologies have no reason to be the same. Schwartz uses compact convergence as a default
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*, ┬Д2, p. 50][schwartz1957]),
which we follow here.

Finally, note that a **sequence** of distributions converges in `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` if and only if it
converges pointwise
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д3, Theor├еme XIII][schwartz1950]).
Due to this fact, some texts endow `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` with the pointwise convergence topology. While this
gives the same converging sequences as the topology of bounded/compact convergence, this is no
longer true for general filters.

## References

* [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*][schwartz1950]
* [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*][schwartz1957]

-/

@[expose] public section

open Set TopologicalSpace
open scoped Distributions CompactConvergenceCLM

variable
  {E : Type*} [NormedAddCommGroup E] [NormedSpace РёЮ E] {╬Е : Opens E}
  {F : Type*} [AddCommGroup F] [Module РёЮ F] [TopologicalSpace F]
  {F' : Type*} [AddCommGroup F'] [Module РёЮ F'] [TopologicalSpace F']
  {n k : РёЋРѕъ}

namespace Distributions

variable [IsTopologicalAddGroup F] [ContinuousSMul РёЮ F]
variable [IsTopologicalAddGroup F'] [ContinuousSMul РёЮ F']
-- variable [NormedAddCommGroup F] [NormedSpace РёЮ F]
-- variable [NormedAddCommGroup F'] [NormedAddCommGroup F']
-- variable [NormedSpace РёЮ F] [NormedSpace РёЮ F']

variable (╬Е n) in
noncomputable def ofFunWithOrder (f : E Рєњ F) (╬╝ : Measure E := by volume_tac) :
    ­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F) :=
  TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinCLM (ContinuousLinearMap.lsmul РёЮ РёЮ) ╬╝ f

variable (╬Е) in
noncomputable def ofFun (f : E Рєњ F) (╬╝ : Measure E := by volume_tac) : ­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F) :=
  ofFunWithOrder ╬Е Ріц f ╬╝

@[simp]
lemma ofFunWithOrder_apply {f : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (hf : LocallyIntegrableOn f ╬Е ╬╝)
    {¤є : TestFunction ╬Е РёЮ Ріц} :
    ofFunWithOrder ╬Е n f ╬╝ ¤є = РѕФ x, ¤є x Рђб f x Рѕѓ╬╝ := by
  simp [ofFunWithOrder, TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinCLM_apply hf]

@[simp]
lemma ofFun_apply {f : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (hf : LocallyIntegrableOn f ╬Е ╬╝)
    {¤є : TestFunction ╬Е РёЮ} :
    ofFun ╬Е f ╬╝ ¤є = РѕФ x, ¤є x Рђб f x Рѕѓ╬╝ := ofFunWithOrder_apply hf

lemma ofFunWithOrder_of_not_locallyIntegrable {f : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E}
    (hf : ┬гLocallyIntegrableOn f ╬Е ╬╝) : ofFunWithOrder ╬Е n f ╬╝ = 0 := by
  ext ¤є
  simp_rw [ofFunWithOrder, TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinCLM,
    TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinLM, hf]
  dsimp
  congr -- TODO: this line used to be not necessary!

lemma ofFun_of_not_locallyIntegrable {f : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (hf : ┬гLocallyIntegrableOn f ╬Е ╬╝) :
    ofFun ╬Е f ╬╝ = 0 := by
  ext ¤є
  simp [ofFun, ofFunWithOrder_of_not_locallyIntegrable hf]

lemma ofFunWithOrder_ae_congr {f f' : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (h : f =рхљ[╬╝.restrict ╬Е] f') :
  ofFunWithOrder ╬Е n f ╬╝ = ofFunWithOrder ╬Е n f' ╬╝ := sorry

lemma ofFun_ae_congr {f f' : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (h : f =рхљ[╬╝.restrict ╬Е] f') :
    ofFun ╬Е f ╬╝ = ofFun ╬Е f' ╬╝ := ofFunWithOrder_ae_congr h

@[simp]
lemma ofFunWithOrder_zero {╬╝ : Measure E} : ofFunWithOrder ╬Е n (0 : E Рєњ F) ╬╝ = 0 := by
  ext ¤є
  simp [ofFunWithOrder, TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinCLM, TestFunction.integralAgainstBilinLM]
  congr -- TODO: this line used to be not necessary!

@[simp]
lemma ofFun_zero {╬╝ : Measure E} : ofFun ╬Е (0 : E Рєњ F) ╬╝ = 0 := by
  ext ¤є
  simp [ofFun]

-- TODO: find a better name!
lemma integrable_smul {f : E Рєњ F} {╬╝ : Measure E} (¤є : TestFunction ╬Е РёЮ Ріц) (hf : LocallyIntegrableOn f (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝) :
    Integrable (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) ╬╝ := by
  have h1 : ¤є.support.compact := by
    simpa using ¤є.isCompactlySupported
  have h2 : ¤є.support Ріє (РєЉ╬Е : Set E) := by
    simpa using ¤є.supportedIn
```

Now we have established that `¤є` has compact support within `╬Е`. We need to show that `fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x` is integrable.

To prove this, we can use the fact that `¤є` is non-zero only on a compact set. This implies that the product `¤є(x) Рђб f(x)` is also integrable.

```tactics
have h3 : LocallyIntegrableOn (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝ := by
  have h4 : LocallyIntegrableOn f (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝ := hf
  have h5 : ¤є.support.compact := h1
  have h6 : ¤є.support Ріє (РєЉ╬Е : Set E) := h2
```

We need to show that the product is locally integrable. Since `¤є` is non-zero only on a compact set, and `f` is locally integrable on `╬Е`, their product is also locally integrable.

```tactics
have h7 : LocallyIntegrableOn (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝ := by
  apply LocallyIntegrableOn.mul_of_support_subset
  exact h4
  all_goals
    try { 
      simpa using h1 
    }
    try { 
      simpa using h6 
    }
```

Now we have shown that `fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x` is locally integrable on `РєЉ╬Е` with respect to `╬╝`. To complete the proof, we need to convert this to the `Integrable` predicate.

```tactics
exact h7
```

Now we have `h3 : LocallyIntegrableOn (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝`. We need to convert this to `Integrable (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) ╬╝`.

```tactics
have h4 : Integrable (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) ╬╝ := by
  have h5 : LocallyIntegrableOn (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) (РєЉ╬Е) ╬╝ := h3
  have h6 : (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) = fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x := by rfl
```

To convert from local integrability to integrability, we need to use the fact that `РєЉ╬Е` is an open set. In a locally compact space, local integrability implies integrability.

```tactics
have h7 : Integrable (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) ╬╝ := by
  apply Real.integrable_of_locally_integrable_of_supportCompact
  exact h5
  all_goals
    try { 
      simpa using h1 
    }
    try { 
      simpa using h6 
    }
```

Now we have `h7 : Integrable (fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x) ╬╝`. This is exactly what we need to prove.

```tactics
exact h7
```

Now we can complete the proof by using the established facts.

```tactics
exact h4
```

The proof is now complete. We have shown that `fun x => ¤є x Рђб f x` is integrable with respect to `╬╝`.

The key insight was that `¤є` has compact support, which implies that the product `¤є(x) Рђб f(x)` is also integrable, given that `f` is locally integrable on `╬Е`.
</think>
