import Mathlib.Analysis.Distribution.TestFunction
import Mathlib.Analysis.LocallyConvex.StrongTopology

/-!
# Distributions

Let `E` be a real **finite-dimensional normed space**, `╬Е` an open subset of `E`,
and `F` a real **locally convex topological vector space**.

An **`F`-valued distribution on `╬Е`** is a continuous `РёЮ`-linear map `T : ­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL[РёЮ] F`,
defined on the space `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)` of real-valued test functions, and taking values in `F`.
In particular, if `­ЮЋю` is an `RCLike` field, `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, ­ЮЋю)` is the usual notion of real or complex
distribution on `╬Е`.

We denote the space of `F`-valued distributions on `╬Е` by `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)`. Topologically,
it is defined as `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL_c[РёЮ] F`, meaning that we endow it with the topology of uniform
convergence on compact subsets of `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)`. In this particular case, this happens to coincide
with the topology of uniform convergence on bounded subsets.
See the implementation notes below for more details.

Right now, this file contains very few mathematical statements.
The theory will be expanded in future PRs.

## Main Declarations

* `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F) = Distribution ╬Е F n` is the space of `F`-valued distributions on `╬Е` with
  order at most `n`. See the implementation notes below for more information about the parameter
  `n : РёЋРѕъ`; in most cases you want to use the space `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F) = Distribution ╬Е F Ріц`.
* `Distribution.mapCLM`: any continuous linear map `A : F РєњL[РёЮ] G` induces a continuous linear
  map `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F) РєњL[РёЮ] ­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, G)`. On locally integrable functions, this corresponds to applying `A`
  pointwise.

## Notation

In the `Distributions` scope, we introduce the following notations:
* `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)`: the space of `F`-valued distributions on the open set `╬Е` with order at most
  `n : РёЋРѕъ`.
* `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)`: the space of `F`-valued distributions on the open set `╬Е`, i.e `­ЮЊЊ'^{Ріц}(╬Е, F)`.

Note that the parameter `n` here lives in `РёЋРѕъ`, unlike the parameter for `ContDiff` which lives
in `WithTop РёЋРѕъ` (to incorporate analytic functions). This means that we can't use the notation
`Рѕъ` introduced for `ContDiff` for our regularity, because it denotes an element of `WithTop РёЋРѕъ`.
We could introduce another notation `Рѕъ` for `Ріц : РёЋРѕъ`, but we believe it would be confusing.

## Implementation Notes

### `abbrev` or `def`

At this point in time, it is not clear wether we should enforce a separation between the API
for `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` and the more generic API about `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL_c[РёЮ] F`.
For now, we have made the "default" choice to implement `Distribution` as an `abbrev`, which means
that we get a lot of instances for free, but also that there is no such separation of APIs.

If this happens to be a bad decision, which will become clear while developing the theory,
do not hesitate to refactor to a `def` instead.

### Vector-valued distributions

The theory of vector-valued distributions is not as well-known as its scalar-valued analog. The
definition we choose is studied in
[L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*][schwartz1957].

Let us give two examples of how we plan to use this level of generality:
* In the short term, this will allow us to define the *Fr├Еchet derivative* of a distribution,
  as a continuous linear map `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F) РєњL[РёЮ] ­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, E РєњL[РёЮ] F)`. Note that, even if `F = РёЮ`,
  the derivative is naturally vector-valued.
* On a longer timescale, we should aim to prove the
  [Schwartz Kernel Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwartz_kernel_theorem), which is
  formulated nicely in terms of vector-valued distributions. Indeed, it says precisely that one
  can (algebraically, at least) identify the spaces `­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓЂ ├Ќ╦б ╬ЕРѓѓ, РёЮ)` and `­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓЂ, ­ЮЊЊ'(╬ЕРѓѓ, РёЮ))`.

### Choice of scalar field

In the literature, it is common to define complex-valued distributions as continuous `Рёѓ`-linear
forms `T : ­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ) РєњL[Рёѓ] Рёѓ`. We use `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL[РёЮ] Рёѓ` instead, that is, we only ever test
against *real-valued* test functions.

This makes no difference mathematically, since `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ)` is the complexification of `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)`,
hence there is a topological isomorphism between `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ) РєњL[РёЮ] F` and `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, Рёѓ) РєњL[Рёѓ] F`
whenever `F` is a complex vector space.

We choose this definition because it avoids adding a base field as an extra parameter.
Instead, we use the generality of vector-valued distributions to our advantage: a complex-valued
distribution is nothing more than a distribution taking values in the real vector-space `Рёѓ`.

### Order of distributions

Based on established practice in the literature, a natural way to express the order of a
distribution would be to introduce a predicate `Distribution.HasOrderAtMost` on the space of all
distributions. Here though, we define a separate space `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` whose elements are precisely
distributions of order at most `n`.

This is not incompatible with the predicate approach: in fact, we think that such a predicate
should eventually become the primary interface for the order of a distribution. However, we believe
that being able to talk about the space `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` is also quite important, for the following
reasons:
* if `T : ­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е,F)` is a distribution whose order is at most `n`, it is natural to test it against
  a `C^n` test function (especially if `n = 0`). This means that we naturally want to consider its
  extension `T'` as an element of `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)`.
* it is often quite easy to keep track of the regularities while *defining* an operation on
  distributions (e. g. differentiation). On the other hand, once you have defined an operation on
  `­ЮЊЊ'^(╬Е, F)`, it can be quite painful to study its relation to order *a posteriori*.

Note that the topology on `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` has no reason to be the subspace topology coming from
`­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)`.

### Choice of topology

Our choice of the compact convergence topology on `­ЮЊЊ'^{n}(╬Е, F)` follows
[L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*, ┬Д2, p. 49][schwartz1957].

Note that, since `­ЮЊЊ(╬Е, РёЮ)` is a Montel space, the topology on `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` is also that of
bounded convergence. Hence, our definition also agrees with
[L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д3][schwartz1950].

When `n` is finite, however, `­ЮЊЊ^{n}(╬Е, РёЮ)` is no longer a Montel space
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д2, p. 71][schwartz1950]), hence
these two topologies have no reason to be the same. Schwartz uses compact convergence as a default
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*, ┬Д2, p. 50][schwartz1957]),
which we follow here.

Finally, note that a **sequence** of distributions converges in `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` if and only if it
converges pointwise
(see [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*, Chapitre III, ┬Д3, Theor├еme XIII][schwartz1950]).
Due to this fact, some texts endow `­ЮЊЊ'(╬Е, F)` with the pointwise convergence topology. While this
gives the same converging sequences as the topology of bounded/compact convergence, this is no
longer true for general filters.

## References

* [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions*][schwartz1950]
* [L. Schwartz, *Th├Еorie des distributions ├а valeurs vectorielles*][schwartz1957]

-/

